[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In computing, a **namespace** is a set of signs (*names*) that are used to identify and refer to objects of various kinds.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A namespace ensures that all of a given set of objects have unique names so that they can be easily identified.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespaces are commonly structured as hierarchies to allow reuse of names in different contexts.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] As an analogy, consider a system of naming of people where each person has a given name, as well as a family name shared with their relatives.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] If the first names of family members are unique only within each family, then each person can be uniquely identified by the combination of first name and family name; there is only one Jane Doe, though there may be many Janes.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Within the namespace of the Doe family, just "Jane" suffices to unambiguously designate this person, while within the "global" namespace of all people, the full name must be used.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Prominent examples for namespaces include file systems, which assign names to files.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Some programming languages organize their variables and subroutines in namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Computer networks and distributed systems assign names to resources, such as computers, printers, websites, and remote files.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Operating systems can partition kernel resources by isolated namespaces to support OS-level virtualization containers.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Similarly, hierarchical file systems organize files in directories.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Each directory is a separate namespace, so that the directories "letters" and "invoices" may both contain a file "to_jane".
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In computer programming, namespaces are typically used to group symbols and identifiers around a given task and to avoid name collisions between multiple identifiers that share the same name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In computer networking, the Domain Name System organizes websites (and other resources) into hierarchical namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Element names are defined by the developer.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This often results in a conflict when trying to mix XML documents from different XML applications.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] If these XML fragments were added together, there would be a name conflict.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Both contain a `<table>...</table>` element, but the elements have different content and meaning.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] An XML parser will not know how to handle these differences.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Name conflicts in XML can easily be avoided using a name prefix.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] The following XML distinguishes between information about the HTML table and furniture by prefixing "h" and "f" at the beginning of the elements.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A name in a namespace consists of a namespace name and a local name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] The namespace name is usually applied as a prefix to the local name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] When local names are used by themselves, name resolution is used to decide which (if any) particular name is alluded to by some particular local name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Delegation of responsibilities between parties is important in real-world applications, such as the structure of the World Wide Web.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespaces allow delegation of identifier assignment to multiple name issuing organisations whilst retaining global uniqueness.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A central Registration authority registers the assigned namespace names allocated.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Each namespace name is allocated to an organisation which is subsequently responsible for the assignment of names in their allocated namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This organisation may be a name issuing organisation that assign the names themselves, or another Registration authority which further delegates parts of their namespace to different organisations.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A naming scheme that allows subdelegation of namespaces to third parties is a **hierarchical namespace**.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A hierarchy is recursive if the syntax for the namespace names is the same for each subdelegation.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] An example of a recursive hierarchy is the Domain name system.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] An example of a non-recursive hierarchy are Uniform Resource Name representing an Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) number.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A namespace name may provide context (scope in computer science) to a name, and the terms are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] However, the context of a name may also be provided by other factors, such as the location where it occurs or the syntax of the name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For many programming languages, namespace is a context for their identifiers.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In an operating system, an example of namespace is a directory.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Each name in a directory uniquely identifies one file or subdirectory.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] As a rule, names in a namespace cannot have more than one meaning; that is, different meanings cannot share the same name in the same namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A namespace is also called a context, because the same name in different namespaces can have different meanings, each one appropriate for its namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] As well as its abstract language technical usage as described above, some languages have a specific keyword used for explicit namespace control, amongst other uses.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A namespace in computer science (sometimes also called a **name scope**) is an abstract container or environment created to hold a logical grouping of unique identifiers or symbols (i.e. names).
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] An identifier defined in a namespace is associated only with that namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] The same identifier can be independently defined in multiple namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] That is, an identifier defined in one namespace may or may not have the same meaning as the same identifier defined in another namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Languages that support namespaces specify the rules that determine to which namespace an identifier (not its definition) belongs.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This concept can be illustrated with an analogy.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Imagine that two companies, X and Y, each assign ID numbers to their employees.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] X should not have two employees with the same ID number, and likewise for Y; but it is not a problem for the same ID number to be used at both companies.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, if Bill works for company X and Jane works for company Y, then it is not a problem for each of them to be employee #123.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In this analogy, the ID number is the identifier, and the company serves as the namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] It does not cause problems for the same identifier to identify a different person in each namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In large computer programs or documents it is common to have hundreds or thousands of identifiers.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespaces (or a similar technique, see Emulating namespaces) provide a mechanism for hiding local identifiers.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] They provide a means of grouping logically related identifiers into corresponding namespaces, thereby making the system more modular.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Data storage devices and many modern programming languages support namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Storage devices use directories (or folders) as namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This allows two files with the same name to be stored on the device so long as they are stored in different directories.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] C++, Python), the identifiers naming namespaces are themselves associated with an enclosing namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Thus, in these languages namespaces can nest, forming a namespace tree.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] At the root of this tree is the unnamed **global namespace**.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] It is possible to use anonymous structs as namespaces in C since C99.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In C++, a namespace is defined with a namespace block.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Within this block, identifiers can be used exactly as they are declared.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Outside of this block, the namespace specifier must be prefixed.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, outside of `namespace abc`, `bar` must be written `abc::bar` to be accessed.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] C++ includes another construct that makes this verbosity unnecessary.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] to a piece of code, the prefix `abc::` is no longer needed.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Identifiers that are not explicitly declared within a namespace are considered to be in the global namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] These identifiers can be used exactly as they are declared, or, since the global namespace is unnamed, the namespace specifier `::` can be prefixed.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, `foo` can also be written `::foo`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespace resolution in C++ is hierarchical.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This means that within the hypothetical namespace `food::soup`, the identifier `Chicken` refers to `food::soup::Chicken`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] If `food::soup::Chicken` doesn't exist, it then refers to `food::Chicken`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] If neither `food::soup::Chicken` nor `food::Chicken` exist, `Chicken` refers to `::Chicken`, an identifier in the global namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespaces in C++ are most often used to avoid naming collisions.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Although namespaces are used extensively in recent C++ code, most older code does not use this facility because it did not exist in early versions of the language.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, the entire C++ Standard Library is defined within `namespace std`, but before standardization many components were originally in the global namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] The `using` statement can be used to import a symbol into the current scope.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] The use of the `using` statements in headers for reasons other than backwards compatibility (e.g., convenience) is considered to be against good code practices, as those `using` statements propagate into all translation units that include the header.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] However, modules do not export `using` statements unless explicitly marked `export`, making `using` statements safer to use.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For instance, one can import a module `wikipedia.project.util` with matching namespace `wikipedia::project::util` and then use `using` statements on symbols from that namespace to simplify verbose namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Unlike other languages like Java or Rust, C++ modules, namespaces and source file structure do not necessarily match, though it is convention to match them for clarity (for example, module `abc.def.uvw.XYZ` matches namespaced class `abc::def::uvw::XYZ` and resides in file `abc/def/uvw/XYZ.cppm`).
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] `using` should be used to simplify verbose nested namespaces when modular translation units are used.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] C++11 introduces *inline namespaces*, which is such that its members are treated as if they are also members of the enclosing namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] It is declared by writing `inline namespace`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] It is akin to an implicit `using namespace` statement, meaning qualifying symbols in it is optional.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] If a namespace `a` contains an inline namespace `b`, which in turn contains another inline namespace `c`, then members of `c` can be accessed as if they were members of `a` or `b`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A primary use case for inline namespaces is ABI compatibility and versioning.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] By placing different versions of an API within distinct inline namespaces (e.g., `v1`, `v2`), and then making the currently desired version inline, library developers can manage ABI compatibility.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] When a new version is released, the inline keyword can be moved to the new version's namespace, allowing users to automatically link against the new version while still enabling access to older versions through explicit qualification.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespaces are heavily used in C# language.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] All .NET framework classes are organized in namespaces, to be used more clearly and to avoid chaos.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Also, custom namespaces are used extensively by programmers, to organize their work and to avoid naming collisions.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This eliminates the need to mention the complete name of all classes in that namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In the above examples, `System` is a namespace, and `Console` and `Convert` are classes defined within `System`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Unlike C++, `using` can only import all symbols in a namespace (much like `using namespace` from C++, `use *` in Rust, or `import *` in Java).
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] It cannot be used to import individual symbols and classes like it is used in Java.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Unlike C++, C# namespaces do not allow relative referencing of symbols.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, the class `Foo.Bar.Baz.Qux` cannot be referred to as `Baz.Qux` even if referred to from within namespace `Foo.Bar`: either the namespace `Foo.Bar.Baz` must be imported to refer to class `Qux`, or `Foo.Bar.Baz.Qux` must be fully qualified.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In Java, the idea of a namespace is embodied in Java packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] All code belongs to a package, although that package need not be explicitly named.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Code from other packages is accessed by prefixing the package name before the appropriate identifier, for example `class String` in `package java.lang` can be referred to as `java.lang.String` (this is known as the fully qualified class name).
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Like C++, Java offers a construct that makes it unnecessary to type the package name (`import`).
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] However, certain features (such as reflection) require the programmer to use the fully qualified name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Unlike C++, namespaces in Java are not hierarchical as to the syntax of the language.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] However, packages are named in a hierarchical manner.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, all packages beginning with `java` are a part of the Java platform—the package `java.lang` contains classes core to the language, and `java.lang.reflect` contains core classes specifically relating to reflection.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In Java (and Ada, C#, and others), namespaces/packages express semantic categories of code.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, in C#, `namespace System` contains code provided by the system (the .NET framework).
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] How specific these categories are and how deep the hierarchies go differ from language to language.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Function and class scopes can be viewed as implicit namespaces that are inextricably linked with visibility, accessibility, and object lifetime.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In Java, packages cannot be partially qualified like they can in C++.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For instance, it is not possible to import the `java` namespace and then refer to `java.util.ArrayList` as `util.ArrayList`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Symbols must either be fully qualified or imported completely into scope.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] `import` statements are not transitive nor can they be deliberately marked `export` like in C++.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] All `import` statements must appear at the beginning of the file, and cannot be written at any other scope.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This is in contrast to C++, where the `std` namespace can be imported by writing `using namespace std;`, and then `std::chrono::system_clock` can be referred to as `chrono::system_clock`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Because Java does not support independent functions outside of classes, static class methods and so-called "utility classes" (classes with private constructors and all methods and fields static) are the equivalent to C++-style namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Some examples are `java.lang.Math`, which contains the constants like `Math.PI` and methods like `Math.sin()`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] `import` statements can be used to import all symbols in a package, called a glob import, which is similar to `using namespace` in C++.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For instance, writing `import java.util.*;` imports all classes in the `java.util` package.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This however, can cause symbol pollution within a file.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Furthermore, using glob import statements on packages that have classes with the same name can cause ambiguity, and will fail to compile.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] However, `java.lang.*` is implicitly imported into all Java source files by default.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Kotlin packages are very similar to Java packages, but unlike Java where only class-like objects may reside directly in a package, any top-level symbol (such as a variable, class, type alias, etc.) may live directly inside a package.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Namespaces were introduced into PHP from version 5.3 onwards.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Naming collision of classes, functions and variables can be avoided.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In PHP, a namespace is defined with a namespace block.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In Python, namespaces are defined by the individual modules, and since modules can be contained in hierarchical packages, then namespaces are hierarchical too.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In general when a module is imported then the names defined in the module are defined via that module's namespace, and are accessed in from the calling modules by using the fully qualified name.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Since this directly imports names (without qualification) it can overwrite existing names with no warnings.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A special form of the statement is `from ... import *` which imports all names defined in the named package directly in the calling module's namespace.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In Rust, a namespace is called a "module" and declared using `mod`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Symbols inside the module are by default private, and cannot be accessed externally, unless declared with the `pub` keyword which exposes them.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Modules can have sub-modules inside of them, allowing for nested namespaces.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Similar to the `using` keyword in C++, Rust has the `use` keyword to import symbols into the current scope.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Writing `mod util;` indicates to the compiler to find either a file named `util.rs` or `util/mod.rs`.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] `crate` in a `use` statement refers to the root of the current "crate" (project), while `super` can be used to refer to the parent module.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] The `use` keyword in Rust is more versatile than its counterpart `using` in C++.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In addition to importing single symbols, symbol aliasing with `as` and glob imports, `use` can import multiple symbols on the same line using braces (which may be nested), import individual namespaces, and do all of the above in a single statement.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In XML, the XML namespace specification enables the names of elements and attributes in an XML document to be unique, similar to the role of namespaces in programming languages.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Using XML namespaces, XML documents may contain element or attribute names from more than one XML vocabulary.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In SAP systems (especially ABAP environments), namespaces are used to prevent naming collisions between standard SAP-delivered objects and customer or partner developments.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] A namespace identifier is delimited with “/” (for example `/MYNS/`) and is reserved via SAP’s namespace registration process.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Once reserved, objects created under that namespace are uniquely identifiable and protected from unintended overwrite by SAP upgrades or imports.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In modern SAP landscapes (such as ABAP in the cloud and HDI containers), namespaces are also used to semantically group development artifacts or bundles.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] In programming languages lacking language support for namespaces, namespaces can be emulated to some extent by using an identifier naming convention.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] For example, C libraries such as libpng often use a fixed prefix for all functions and variables that are part of their exposed interface.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] This naming convention provides reasonable assurance that the identifiers are unique and can therefore be used in larger programs without naming collisions.
[src:dependency-confusion/namespace] Likewise, many packages originally written in Fortran (e.g., BLAS, LAPACK) reserve the first few letters of a function's name to indicate the group to which the function belongs.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] It consists of a command line client, also called npm, and an online database of public and paid-for private packages, called the npm registry.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The registry is accessed via the client, and the available packages can be browsed and searched via the npm website.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The package manager and the registry are managed by npm, Inc.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Although "npm" is commonly understood to be an abbreviation of "Node Package Manager", it is officially a recursive backronymic abbreviation for "npm is not an acronym".
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] npm can manage packages that are local dependencies of a particular project, as well as globally-installed JavaScript tools.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] When used as a dependency manager for a local project, npm can install, in one command, all the dependencies of a project through the `package.json` file.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The *npx* command, which is an acronym for *Node Package eXecuter*, executes packages without installing them.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] npm's command-line interface client allows users to consume and distribute JavaScript modules that are available in the registry.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In npm version 6, the audit feature was introduced to help developers identify and fix security vulnerabilities in installed packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The source of security vulnerabilities were taken from reports found on the Node Security Platform (NSP) and has been integrated with npm since npm's acquisition of NSP.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Packages in the registry are in ECMAScript Module (ESM) or CommonJS format and include a metadata file in JSON format.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Over 3.1 million packages are available in the main npm registry.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The registry does not have any vetting process for submission, which means that packages found there can potentially be low quality, insecure, or malicious.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Instead, npm relies on user reports to take down packages if they violate policies by being low quality, insecure, or malicious. npm exposes statistics including number of downloads and number of depending packages to assist developers in judging the quality of packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Internally npm relies on the NoSQL Couch DB to manage publicly available data.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] npm (originally short for Node Package Manager) was created in 2010 by Isaac Z.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Schlueter as a response to existing module packaging systems in the JavaScript ecosystem, which he considered to be inadequate.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Schlueter was influenced by earlier tools such as PEAR for PHP and CPAN for Perl, and aimed to develop a lightweight, community-oriented package manager designed for the Node.js runtime.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] npm was introduced as a more capable alternative to an earlier shell script-based tool named pm, which had limited features for managing Node.js packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The first version of npm was released on January 12, 2010.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Over time, npm was increasingly adopted within the Node.js developer community.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Its ease of use, speed, and ability to distribute reusable code contributed to its widespread usage as a package manager.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] It played a significant role in the development of the JavaScript ecosystem by enabling efficient dependency management and sharing of open-source libraries.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In 2014, the company npm, Inc. was established in Oakland, California by Schlueter and Laurie Voss to oversee the maintenance of the npm registry and to provide related services.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In July 2018, Bryan Bogensberger was appointed as CEO of npm, Inc.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] During his tenure, the company faced both technical and community challenges, including concerns related to registry performance and organizational transparency.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Voss departed the company in July 2019, followed by Bogensberger in September of the same year.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In March 2020, npm, Inc. was acquired by GitHub, a subsidiary of Microsoft.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The acquisition was presented as a step toward improving the infrastructure of the npm registry and strengthening integration with GitHub's developer tools.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Post-acquisition, GitHub committed to keeping the public npm registry free to use and open to the developer community.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] It also announced enhancements including improved security features, better command-line tooling, and publishing support via GitHub Actions.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] As of 2025, npm remains one of the most widely used software package registries, hosting a substantial number of open-source packages and serving billions of downloads on a regular basis.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] It continues to serve as a central infrastructure component for JavaScript and web development workflows.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In March 2016, a package called `left-pad` was unpublished as the result of a naming dispute between Azer Koçulu, an individual software engineer, and Kik.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The package was immensely popular on the platform, being depended on by thousands of projects and reaching 15 million downloads prior to its removal.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Several projects critical to the JavaScript ecosystem including Babel and Webpack depended on `left-pad` and were rendered unusable.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Although the package was republished three hours later, it caused widespread disruption, leading npm to change its policies regarding unpublishing to prevent a similar event in the future.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In November 2018, it was discovered that a malicious package had been added as a dependency to version 3.3.6 of the popular package `event-stream`.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The malicious package, called `flatmap-stream`, contained an encrypted payload that stole bitcoins from certain applications.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In May 2021, `pac-resolver`, an npm package that received over 3 million downloads per week, was discovered to have a remote code execution vulnerability.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The vulnerability resulted from how the package handled config files, and was fixed in versions 5 and greater.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In January 2022, the maintainer of the popular package `colors` pushed changes printing garbage text in an infinite loop.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In March 2022, developer Brandon Nozaki Miller, maintainer of the `node-ipc` package, added `peacenotwar` as a dependency to the package.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] `peacenotwar` recursively overwrites an affected machine's hard drive contents with the heart emoji if they have a Belarusian or Russian IP address.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The package also leaves a text file on the machine containing a message in protest of the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Vue.js, which uses `node-ipc` as a dependency, did not pin its dependencies to a safe version, meaning that some users of Vue.js had the `peacenotwar` package if they were using its latest version.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The package was also briefly present as a dependency in version 3.1 of Unity Hub.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] However, a hotfix was released the same day to remove the dependency.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In May 2023, several npm packages including `bignum` were found to be exploited, stealing user credentials and information from affected machines.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Researchers discovered that these packages had been compromised through an exploit involving Amazon S3 buckets and the `node-gyp` command line tool.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In September 2025, up to 18 popular npm packages were compromised with malware as part of a supply chain attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Packages were compromised through a phishing attack on the package maintainers.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] After the account was compromised attackers began to publish packages with the malware.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] The malware intercepted cryptocurrency transactions within the browser, redirecting the transactions to the attacker's accounts.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Also in September 2025, a self-replicating worm nicknamed Shai-Hulud appeared that steals GitHub developer credentials from affected systems to spread itself to other projects.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] As of September 16, the worm affected more than 187 packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] In November 2025, Amazon Web Services researchers discovered over 150,000 packages hosted on npm that were connected to a Tea blockchain token farming campaign.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] From May to June 2026, various software supply chain attacks occurred via a self-spreading worm called Mini Shai-Hulud, attributed to hacker group TeamPCP, affecting companies such as GitHub, OpenAI, and Mercor.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] There are a number of open-source alternatives to npm for installing modular JavaScript, including pnpm, Yarn, Bun and Deno.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] Deno and Bun also provide a JavaScript runtime, while only Deno operates independently from npm Registry or any centralized repository and its support of npm registry is still a subject of ongoing work in progress as of January 2024.
[src:dependency-confusion/npm] They are all compatible with the public npm registry and use it by default, but provide different client-side experiences, usually focused on improving performance and determinism compared to the npm client.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:dependency-confusion/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:dependency-confusion/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] A **supply chain attack** is a cyber-attack that seeks to damage an organization by targeting less secure elements in the supply chain.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can occur in any industry, from the financial sector, oil industry, to a government sector.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can happen in software or hardware.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Cybercriminals typically tamper with the manufacturing or distribution of a product by installing malware or hardware-based spying components.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Symantec's 2019 Internet Security Threat Report states that supply chain attacks increased by 78 percent in 2018.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a system of activities involved in handling, distributing, manufacturing, and processing goods in order to move resources from a vendor into the hands of the final consumer.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a complex network of interconnected players governed by supply and demand.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Alternatively, the term can be used to describe attacks exploiting the software supply chain, in which an apparently low-level or unimportant software component used by other software can be used to inject malicious code into the larger software that depends on the component.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In a more general sense, a supply chain attack may not necessarily involve electronics.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In 2010 when burglars gained access to the pharmaceutical giant Eli Lilly's supply warehouse, by drilling a hole in the roof and loading $80 million worth of prescription drugs into a truck, they could also have been said to carry out a supply chain attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] However, this article will discuss cyber attacks on physical supply networks that rely on technology; hence, a supply chain attack is a method used by cyber-criminals.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Generally, supply chain attacks on information systems begin with an advanced persistent threat (APT) that determines a member of the supply network with the weakest cyber security in order to affect the target organization.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Hackers don't usually directly target a larger entity, such as the United States Government, but instead target the entity's software.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The third-party software is often less protected, leading to an easier target.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] According to an investigation produced by Verizon Enterprise, 92% of the cyber security incidents analyzed in their survey occurred among small firms.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain networks are considered to be particularly vulnerable due to their multiple interconnected components.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] APTs can often gain access to sensitive information by physically tampering with the production of the product.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Poorly managed supply chain management systems can become significant hazards for cyber attacks, which can lead to a loss of sensitive customer information, disruption of the manufacturing process, and could damage a company's reputation.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Wired reported a connecting thread in recent software supply chain attacks, as of 3 May 2019.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] These have been surmised to have spread from infected, pirated, popular compilers posted on pirate websites.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] That is, corrupted versions of Apple's Xcode and Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] At the end of 2013, Target, a US retailer, was hit by one of the largest data breaches in the history of the retail industry.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Between 27 November and 15 December 2013, Target's American brick-and-mortar stores experienced a data hack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Around 40 million customers' credit and debit cards became susceptible to fraud after malware was introduced into the POS system in over 1,800 stores.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The data breach of Target's customer information saw a direct impact on the company's profit, which fell 46 percent in the fourth quarter of 2013.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Six months prior the company began installing a $1.6 million cyber security system.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Target had a team of security specialists to monitor its computers constantly.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Nonetheless, the supply chain attack circumvented these security measures.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] It is believed that cyber criminals infiltrated a third party supplier to gain access to Target's main data network.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Although not officially confirmed, investigation officials suspect that the hackers first broke into Target's network on 15 November 2013 using passcode credentials stolen from Fazio Mechanical Services, a Pennsylvania-based provider of HVAC systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Ninety lawsuits have been filed against Target by customers for carelessness and compensatory damages.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Target spent around $61 million responding to the breach, according to its fourth-quarter report to investors.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is a computer worm that is widely believed to be a joint U.S.-Israeli cyber operation, though neither government has officially confirmed involvement.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The worm specifically targets industrial control systems, particularly those that automate electromechanical processes, such as factory machinery and nuclear enrichment equipment.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was designed to manipulate programmable logic controllers (PLCs), disrupting industrial equipment by issuing unauthorized commands while simultaneously feeding falsified operations data to monitoring systems to conceal its activity.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is widely believed to have been developed to disrupt Iran's enriched uranium programs.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Kevin Hogan, Senior Director of Security Response at Symantec, stated that most infections occurred in Iran.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Analysts suggest that its primary target was the Natanz uranium enrichment facility.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was initially introduced into Iran's Natanz facility via infected USB flash drives, requiring physical access to the target network.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] According to reports, engineers or maintenance workers, either knowingly or unknowingly, facilitated its entry into the plant.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Once inside, the worm spread autonomously, exploiting multiple zero-day vulnerabilities in Windows systems to propagate across networked machines running Siemens industrial control software.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In recent years malware known as Suceful, Plotus, Tyupkin and GreenDispenser have affected automated teller machines globally, especially in Russia and Ukraine.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] GreenDispenser specifically gives attackers the ability to walk up to an infected ATM system and remove its cash vault.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] When installed, GreenDispenser may display an 'out of service' message on the ATM, but attackers with the right access credentials can drain the ATM's cash vault and remove the malware from the system using an untraceable delete process.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The other types of malware usually behave in a similar fashion, capturing magnetic stripe data from the machine's memory storage and instructing the machines to withdraw cash.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attacks require a person with insider access, such as an ATM technician or anyone else with a key to the machine, to place the malware on the ATM.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Tyupkin malware active in March 2014 on more than 50 ATMs at banking institutions in Eastern Europe, is believed to have also spread at the time to the U.S., India, and China.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The malware affects ATMs from major manufacturers running Microsoft Windows 32-bit operating systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The malware displays information on how much money is available in every machine and allows an attacker to withdraw 40 notes from the selected cassette of each ATM.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In June 2017, the financial software M.E.Doc, widely used in Ukraine, was identified by security researchers as a likely initial vector for the spread of the NotPetya malware.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers, including those from Microsoft, indicated that NotPetya infections may have originated from a compromised update issued through M.E.Doc.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Some analysts described this as a supply chain attack, though the exact method of compromise was not definitively identified.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The software's developers denied the claim but later deleted their statement and stated that they were cooperating with investigators.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya was initially identified as ransomware because it encrypted hard drives and displayed a ransom demand in bitcoin.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] However, the email account used to provide decryption keys was shut down, leaving victims without a way to recover their files.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Unlike WannaCry, NotPetya had no built-in kill switch, making it harder to stop.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected multiple industries in Ukraine, including banks, an airport, the Kyiv Metro, pharmaceutical companies, and Chernobyl's radiation detection systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] It also spread globally, impacting organizations in Russia, the United Kingdom, India, and the United States.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya spread using EternalBlue, a vulnerability originally developed by the U.S.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] National Security Agency (NSA) and later leaked.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] EternalBlue had previously been used in the WannaCry cyberattack in May 2017.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This exploit enabled NotPetya to spread through the Windows Server Message Block (SMB) protocol.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The malware also used PsExec and the Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to spread within networks.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Due to these exploits, once a device on a network was infected, the malware could rapidly spread to other connected systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Ukrainian police stated that M.E.Doc employees could face criminal liability for negligence, citing repeated warnings from antivirus firms about security vulnerabilities in the company's cybersecurity infrastructure.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The head of Ukraine's CyberPolice, Colonel Serhiy Demydiuk, alleged that M.E.Doc had been repeatedly warned by security firms about weaknesses in its systems but failed to act, stating, "They knew about it." Authorities later reported that M.E.Doc cooperated with investigators.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] From August 21 until September 5, 2018 British Airways was under attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The British Airways website payment section contained a code that harvested customer payment data.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The injected code was written specifically to route credit card information to a domain baways.com, which could erroneously be thought to belong to British Airways.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is the entity believed to be behind the attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is a name attributed to multiple hacker groups that use skimming practices in order to steal customer information through online payment processes.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Approximately 380,000 customers had their personal and financial data compromised as a result of the attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] British Airways later reported in October, 2018 that an additional 185,000 customers may have had their personal information stolen as well.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The 2020 SolarWinds cyberattack was linked to a supply chain compromise targeting the IT infrastructure company SolarWinds, which provided software used by multiple U.S. federal institutions, including networks within the National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA).
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Russian hackers compromised Orion, a widely used network management software developed by SolarWinds, by injecting malicious code into software updates.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This allowed them to gain unauthorized access to numerous organizations, including multiple U.S. government agencies that relied on Orion for IT monitoring and management.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Department of Homeland Security issued Emergency Directive 21-01, "*Mitigate SolarWinds Orion Code Compromise",* requiring affected federal agencies to disconnect compromised Windows host OS instances from their enterprise domain and rebuild those hosts using trusted sources.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] These compromised systems had been running SolarWinds Orion.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In December 2020, FireEye identified a cyber breach involving the SolarWinds Orion software, which had been compromised prior to its discovery.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft was among the organizations affected, detecting and removing malicious files linked to the breach.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has since collaborated with FireEye as part of an ongoing investigation into the incident.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The cyberattack targeted supply chain software used across various industries, including government, consulting, technology, telecommunications, and extractive sectors in North America, Europe, Asia and the Middle East.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] None of the Microsoft repositories contained production credentials.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The repositories were secured in December, and those attacks ceased in January.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] However, in March 2021 more than 20,000 US organizations were compromised through a back door that was installed via flaws in Exchange Server.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The affected organizations use self-hosted e-mail (on-site rather than cloud-based) such as credit unions, town governments, and small businesses.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The flaws were patched on 2 March 2021, but by 5 March 2021 only 10% of the compromised organizations had implemented the patch; the back door remains open.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The US officials are attempting to notify the affected organizations which are smaller than the organizations that were affected in December 2020.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has updated its Indicators of Compromise tool and has released emergency mitigation measures for its Exchange Server flaws.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attacks on SolarWinds and Microsoft software are currently thought to be independent, as of March 2021.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Indicators of Compromise tool allows customers to scan their Exchange Server log files for compromise.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] At least 10 attacking groups are using the Exchange Server flaws.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Web shells can remain on a patched server; this still allows cyberattacks based on the affected servers.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] As of 12 March 2021 exploit attempts are doubling every few hours, according to Check Point Research, some in the name of security researchers themselves.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] By 14 April 2021 the FBI had completed a covert cyber operation to remove the web shells from afflicted servers and was informing the servers' owners of what had been done.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021 Microsoft identified 3000 malicious emails to 150 organizations in 24 countries, that were launched by a group that Microsoft has denoted 'Nobelium'.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Many of those emails were blocked before delivery.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] 'Nobelium' gained access to a Constant Contact "email marketing account used by the US Agency for International Development (USAID)".
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers assert that 'Nobelium' crafts spear-phishing email messages which get clicked on by unsuspecting users; the links then direct installation of malicious 'Nobelium' code to infect the users' systems, making them subject to ransom, espionage, disinformation, etc.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The US government has identified 'Nobelium' as stemming from Russia's Federal Security Service.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] By July 2021 the US government is expected to name the initiator of the Exchange Server attacks: "China's Ministry of State Security has been using criminal contract hackers".
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In September 2021 the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) enforcement staff have requested that any companies which have downloaded any compromised SolarWinds updates, voluntarily turn over data to the SEC if they have installed the compromised updates on their servers.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In July 2022 SessionManager, a malicious module hosted by IIS (installed by default on Exchange Servers), was discovered to have infected Exchange Servers since March 2021; SessionManager searches memory for passwords, and downloads new modules, to hijack the server.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Mandiant, a security firm, has shown that nation-state-sponsored groups, once they have gained access to corporate clouds, can now exploit Security assertion markup language (SAML), to gain federated authentication to Active Directory and similar services, at will.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Once the attackers gain access, they are able to infiltrate any information or assets belonging to the organization.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This is because this technique allows attackers to pose as any member of the targeted organization.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] These attacks are progressively becoming more desirable to malicious actors as companies and agencies continue to move assets to cloud services.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In 2020, SolarWinds was subject to what is described as the first documented Golden SAML attack, often referred to as "Solorigate".
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] A malicious actor infected the source code of a software update with a backdoor code made to look legitimate.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Customers began installing the faulty update to their systems, ultimately affecting over 18,000 individuals globally.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected a number of United States government agencies and private sector agencies as well.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021, a ransomware attack on Colonial Pipeline forced a temporary shutdown of a major fuel distribution network, disrupting the supply of gasoline, diesel, and jet fuel to the U.S.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Biden administration invoked emergency powers to prevent shortages, while experts described the incident as the worst-ever cyberattack on U.S. infrastructure.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack, attributed to the Russian-linked cybercriminal group DarkSide, raised concerns about vulnerabilities in critical energy systems, as fuel traders sought alternative supply routes and fears of price spikes emerged.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] On June 16, 2021, President Biden stated to President Putin that cyberattacks on 16 critical infrastructure sectors were off-limits and said that the U.S. would respond to future cyber threats.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The 16 critical infrastructure sectors, as designated by the U.S.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), include energy, food and agriculture, emergency services, healthcare, and other essential industries such as financial services, communications, and transportation systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] On 2 July 2021, about 60 managed service providers (MSPs) and their customers became victims of a ransomware attack perpetrated by the REvil group, causing downtime for over 1,000 companies.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] REvil carried out the attack by exploiting a vulnerability in VSA (Virtual System Administrator), a remote monitoring and management software package developed by Kaseya.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This was a form of supply chain attack on a software supply chain.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] REvil demanded about 70 million USD in Bitcoin as a ransom.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] On 23 July 2021, Kaseya announced that it had received a universal decryptor tool from a "trusted third party", and it helped customers restore their data.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Two suspects were identified and one sentenced.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In March 2023, the voice and video chat app 3CX Phone System was thought to have been subject to a supply chain attack due to detection of malicious activity on the software.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The app is used in a wide variety of industries from food to automotive and an attack has the potential to impact hundreds of thousands of users worldwide.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The malware infects the host device through the installation process, acting as a Trojan horse virus spread through both Mac OS and Microsoft installers.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] They employed an infostealer through a malicious payload that connected to a C2 server controlled by the threat actor.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack utilized the Gopuram backdoor, originally discovered by the Russian cybersecurity company Kaspersky in 2020.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The use of this backdoor suggested that the attack was executed by the North Korean cybercrime group known as Lazarus due to their use of this same backdoor in a 2020 attack against a South Asian cryptocurrency company.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Gopuram backdoor has been utilized in other past attacks against cryptocurrency agencies, which Lazarus has been known to target.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In July 2023, Chinese state-sponsored hackers targeted the United States Department of State, hacking several government employees' Microsoft email accounts, which gave them access to classified information.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] They stole information from about 60,000 emails from several Department of State employees.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Department of State officials have stated that the information stolen includes "victims' travel itineraries and diplomatic deliberations".
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] If used in a malicious manner, this information could be used to monitor important government officials and track United States communications that are meant to be confidential.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Department of State hack occurred due to vulnerabilities in Microsoft Exchange Server, classifying it as a supply-chain attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In March 2024, a backdoor in xz/liblzma in XZ Utils was suspected, with malicious code known to be in version 5.6.0 and 5.6.1.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] While the exploit remained dormant unless a specific third-party patch of the SSH server is used, under the right circumstances this interference could potentially enable a malicious actor to break sshd authentication and gain unauthorized access to the entire system remotely.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The list of affected Linux distributions includes Debian unstable, Fedora Rawhide, Kali Linux, and OpenSUSE Tumbleweed.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Most Linux distributions that followed a stable release update model were not affected, since they were carrying older versions of xz.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Arch Linux issued an advisory for users to update immediately, although it also noted that Arch's OpenSSH package does not include the common third-party patch necessary for the backdoor.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] FreeBSD is not affected by this attack, as all supported FreeBSD releases include versions of xz that predate the affected releases and the attack targets Linux's glibc.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] On October 31, 2024, cybersecurity researchers from several security firms such as Phylum, Socket, and Checkmarx detected an attack on users of the open-source Node Package Manager (NPM) library.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Unidentified attackers published more than 287 packages in an attempt to trick users of the platform into downloading malicious code.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack used a technique called typosquatting, which copies the names of legitimate packages closely, tricking unsuspecting developers into accidentally downloading the wrong one.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] For the package Fetch-mock-jest, the attacker rearranged the order of the words and misspelled the word fetch creating the name "jest-fet-mock".
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Based on the kind of packages mimicked, researchers believe this attack widely targeted software developers using NPM.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Packages targeted are mostly mock HTTP requests and cryptocurrency-related, including Puppeteer, Bignum.js, and Fetch-mock-jest, which are mainly used in development environments.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Phylum researchers noted that these typosquatted packages seemed normal at first glance, but upon closer inspection, they contained obfuscated code that could not be understood.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] After de-obfuscating the code, researchers found that after the malicious package is mistakenly downloaded it automatically runs a script that interacts with an Ethereum smart contract to retrieve the IP addresses of the command and control server (C2) used by the attackers.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The script then identifies the operating system used by the victim machine and downloads compatible malware from the IP address it received from the contract.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This malware maintains persistent communication with the attacker's C2 server, periodically leaking the user's system information such as the operating system version, GPU, CPU, the amount of memory on the machine, and username.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Checkmarkx researcher Yahud Gelb explains that if researchers attempt to take down a C2 server at a specific IP address, the attacker can just update the Ethereum contract so that it returns a different address.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] When describing the mechanism behind the contract he wrote: "Think of a smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain as a public bulletin board – anyone can read what's posted, but only the owner has the ability to update it".
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This complicates the issue because the malware can always query the smart contract to update the stored address of the C2 server in case the current one has been taken down by authorities.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Researchers worried that several companies' software development supply chains can be put at risk when attackers typosquat them.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] They elaborate that the untraceable nature of the attack combined with its precisely engineered methods of persistence only adds to the looming threat.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Furthermore, company employees usually have elevated system privileges and access to CI/CD pipelines when using development environments, further endangering the company's and their customer's data.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] They warned that developers who use npm packages like the ones above at any stage of the software development lifecycle must take caution and implement robust dependency scanning before performing any installations.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] There is little to no information on the attackers' identity or their motive.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] However, researchers did find error messages written in Russian within the de-obfuscated code of the malicious packages, but they speculate that this could be a misdirect set up by the real culprits trying to throw off any suspicions.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, the popular text editor Notepad++ was subjected to a sophisticated supply chain attack when threat actors compromised the application's update infrastructure at the hosting provider level.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack, which began in June 2025 and continued through December 2025, involved the interception and redirection of update traffic from the official notepad-plus-plus.org domain to attacker-controlled servers.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] According to the Notepad++ maintainer, the shared hosting server was fully compromised until September 2, 2025, after which attackers maintained access to internal service credentials until December 2, 2025, allowing them to continue redirecting update traffic.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Kaspersky researchers identified three primary execution chains used between July and October 2025, with attackers constantly changing command-and-control server addresses, downloaders, and final payloads to evade detection.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Security firm Rapid7 attributed the campaign to the Lotus Blossom group (also known as Violet Typhoon or APT31), linking the attacks to infrastructure and tactics previously observed in campaigns targeting cryptocurrency companies and critical infrastructure.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] On January 20, 2026, the eScan antivirus software, developed by Indian cybersecurity firm MicroWorld Technologies, was compromised in a supply chain attack when threat actors breached one of the company's regional update servers and deployed malware to customer systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The incident lasted approximately one hour before being detected by security researchers at Morphisec and Kaspersky.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The attack primarily affected users in South Asia, including India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, and the Philippines.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Attackers replaced the legitimate Reload.exe component of eScan with a malicious executable that disabled future antivirus updates and downloaded additional payloads from command-and-control servers.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This marked the second breach of eScan's infrastructure, following a 2024 incident where North Korean state-sponsored group Kimsuky exploited the same update mechanism to deploy backdoors and cryptocurrency miners.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] No attribution has been made for the 2026 attack.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] On 12 May 2021, Executive Order 14028 (the EO), *Improving the nation's cybersecurity*, tasked NIST as well as other US government agencies with enhancing the cybersecurity of the United States.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Comprehensive National Cybersecurity Initiative and the Cyberspace Policy Review passed by the Bush and Obama administrations respectively, direct U.S. federal funding for development of multi-pronged approaches for global supply chain risk management.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] According to Adrian Davis of the Technology Innovation Management Review, securing organizations from supply chain attacks begins with building cyber-resilient systems.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain resilience is, according to supply chain risk management expert Donal Walters, "the ability of the supply chain to cope with unexpected disturbances" and one of its characteristics is a company-wide recognition of where the supply chain is most susceptible to infiltration.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain management plays a crucial role in creating effective supply chain resilience.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In March 2015, under the Conservative and Liberal democratic government coalition, the UK Department for Business outlined new efforts to protect SMEs from cyber attacks, which included measures to improve supply chain resilience.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The UK government has produced the Cyber Essentials Scheme, which trains firms for good practices to protect their supply chain and overall cyber security.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, a study by the Austrian Chamber of Commerce (WKO) and AV-Comparatives identified what cybersecurity firms should do to assure their customers about supply chain security.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] This includes disclosing a software bill of materials, maintaining transparent data storage practices, providing detailed incident reports, and offering facilities where customers can inspect source codes and updates for the cybersecurity product.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Only 3 of the 14 vendors examined provided such assurances.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain attacks have prompted regulatory bodies to address third-party risk management requirements.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] The Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued Binding Operational Directive 22-01, requiring federal agencies to remediate known exploited vulnerabilities within specified timeframes.
[src:dependency-confusion/supply-chain-attack] NIST Special Publication 800-161 *Cybersecurity Supply Chain Risk Management Practices* provides a framework for organizations to identify, assess, and mitigate supply chain risks throughout the system development life cycle.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The objective of the cheat sheet is to provide a proposal of approach regarding the handling of vulnerable third-party dependencies when they are detected, and this, depending on different situation.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Proposals mentioned in this cheat sheet are not silver-bullet (recipes that work in all situations) yet can be used as a foundation and adapted to your context.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Most of the projects use third-party dependencies to delegate handling of different kind of operations, *e.g.* generation of document in a specific format, HTTP communications, data parsing of a specific format, etc.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's a good approach because it allows the development team to focus on the real application code supporting the expected business feature.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The dependency brings forth an expected downside where the security posture of the real application is now resting on it.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's highly recommended to perform automated analysis of the dependencies from the birth of the project.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Indeed, if this task is added at the middle or end of the project, it can imply a huge amount of work to handle all the issues identified and that will in turn impose a huge burden on the development team and might to blocking the advancement of the project at hand.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In the rest of the cheat sheet, when we refer to *development team* then we assume that the team contains a member with the required application security skills or can refer to someone in the company having these kind of skills to analyse the vulnerability impacting the dependency.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's important to keep in mind the different ways in which a security issue is handled after its discovery.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here, the vulnerability is always referenced in the CVE global database used, generally, by the detection tools as one of the several input sources used.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] See a description here, into the section named **Computers** about **Computer Security**.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The researcher decides to release all the information including exploitation code/method on services like Full Disclosure mailing list, Exploit-DB.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here a CVE is not always created then the vulnerability is not always in the CVE global database causing the detection tools to be potentially blind about unless the tools use other input sources.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, it's possible to decide to accept the risk represented by the security issue.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] However, this decision must be taken by the Chief Risk Officer (fallback possible to Chief Information Security Officer) of the company based on technical feedback from the development team that have analyzed the issue (see the *Cases* section) as well as the CVEs CVSS score indicators.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, the development team can meet one of the situations (named *Case* in the rest of the cheat sheet) presented in the sub sections below.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the vulnerably impact a transitive dependency then the action will be taken on the direct dependency of the project because acting on a transitive dependency often impact the stability of the application.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Acting on a on a transitive dependency require the development team to fully understand the complete relation/communication/usage from the project first level dependency until the dependency impacted by the security vulnerability, this task is very time consuming.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Patched version of the component has been released by the provider.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests exist for the features of the application using the impacted dependency allowing to validate that the feature is operational.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Update the version of the dependency in the project on a testing environment.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that it will take a while to fix the issue and, so, a patched version will not be available before months.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If a workaround is provided, it should be applied and validated on the testing environment, and thereafter deployed to production.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has given the team a list of the impacted functions, protective code must wrap the calls to these functions to ensure that the input and the output data is safe.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Moreover, security devices, such as the Web Application Firewall (WAF), can handle such issues by protecting the internal applications through parameter validation and by generating detection rules for those specific libraries.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Yet, in this cheat sheet, the focus is set on the application level in order to patch the vulnerability as close as possible to the source.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided nothing about the vulnerability, Case 3 can be applied skipping the *step 2* of this case.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] We assume here that, at least, the CVE has been provided.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided the team with the exploitation code, and the team made a security wrapper around the vulnerable library/code, execute the exploitation code in order to ensure that the library is now secure and doesn't affect the application.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exist for the application, run them to verify that the protection code added does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Add a comment in the project *README* explaining that the issue (specify the related CVE) is handled during the waiting time of a patched version because the detection tool will continue to raise an alert on this dependency.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that they cannot fix the issue, so no patched version will be released at all (applies also if provider does not want to fix the issue or does not answer at all).
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In this case the only information given to the development team is the CVE.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Nothing specific because here we are in a *patch yourself* condition.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In all cases, here, we need to handle the vulnerability right now.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] As we know the vulnerable dependency, we know where it is used in the application (if it's a transitive dependency then we can identify the first level dependency using it using the IDE built-in feature or the dependency management system used (Maven, Gradle, NuGet, npm, etc.).
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Note that IDE is also used to identify the calls to the dependency.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying calls to this dependency is fine but it is the first step.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team still lacks information on what kind of patching needs to be performed.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] To obtain these information, the team uses the CVE content to know which kind of vulnerability affects the dependency.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The `description` property provides the answer: SQL injection, Remote Code Execution, Cross-Site Scripting, Cross-Site Request Forgery, etc.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] After identifying the above 2 points, the team is aware of the type of patching that needs to be taken (Case 2 with the protective code) and where to add it.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team has an application using the Jackson API in a version exposed to the CVE-2016-3720.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Based on these information, the team determines that the necessary patching will be to add a pre-validation of any XML data passed to the Jakson API to prevent XML external entity (XXE) vulnerability.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If possible, create a unit test that mimics the vulnerability in order to ensure that the patch is effective and have a way to continuously ensure that the patch is in place during the evolution of the project.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exists for the application then run them to verify that the patch does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider collaborates with you after being notified of the vulnerability.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Inform the provider about the vulnerability by sharing the post with them.
[src:dependency-confusion/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] This section lists several tools that can used to analyze the dependencies used by a project in order to detect the vulnerabilities.
